Project 3 Client Report

Alvin Thomas

12/1/2019

Introduction

The Urban Ministries of Durham (UMD) fights poverty and homeless by offering food, shelter, and a future to neighbors in need. Their mission is accomplished through three primary programs: a community shelter to house homeless neighbors, a community cafe that provides hot and cold meals three times a day, and a food pantry and clothing closet.

During the 2017-2018 fiscal year, UMD provided 54,378 nights of shelter to homeless neighbors (792 unique individuals), served 248,028 meals through the community cafe, and provided clothing and groceries to over 500 households per month. Importantly, they ended homelessness for 243 individuals.

In collaboration with Biostatistics 611, a course titled Introduction to Data Science at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, UMD released several datasets of services provided.

Study Aim

The purpose of this project is describe the population served by UMDs emergency shelter. We will also assess the total amount of time spent at the shelter by demographic groups and the reasons for leaving.

Client Gender

The most common gender identifier is male. There are some that identify as a gender other than male or female. It is important to recognize these individuals and ensure inclusive langauge around gender to support all neighbors.

Client Race

The most common primary race (based on distinct HUD categories) was Black or African American. There were also some white and Native American neighbors that utilized the shelter during the study period.

Client Veteran Status

The majority of neighbors in the UMD shelter were not Veterans.

Client Veteran Status and Age

Neighbors that were also veterans were slightly older than neighbors who were not veterans.

Client Insurance Status

There were a reasonable number of neighbors with insurance, but the majority did not have insurance at the time of entry.

Reasons for Leaving

Conclusion

We have described basic characterisics of the UMD neighbors utilizing shelter services. Veterans are more likely to be older than non-Veteran neighbors. The reason for leaving the program is strongly related to the length of time at the shelter.
